President Barack Obama has proclaimed April 4-10, 2016, as National Public Health Week. In his proclamation, he emphasizes the importance of public health in ensuring the well-being and security of the nation. He highlights the Affordable Care Act, First Lady Michelle Obama's Let's Move! initiative, efforts to address prescription opioid abuse and mental health, and steps taken to address gun violence. The President also discusses the impact of climate change on public health and the United States' commitment to reducing greenhouse gas emissions. He mentions the need for international cooperation in addressing public health challenges such as antibiotic resistance and the spread of infectious diseases. The proclamation calls on citizens, government agencies, businesses, non-profit organizations, and other groups to take action to improve the health of the nation.